Q15_5_TEXT: It is a combination of not enough affordable housing and not enough quality housing. Grinnell is a high market for what you purchase. Many of the new builds lack the quality that you would expect and the price per square foot even before the current national/local rise in the market. We have focused on low income housing while neglecting quality family homes to bring more families into our community. Many of the affordable homes have been neglected in maintenance and require a great amount of work and financial investment to provide families with a quality home.
Q18_5_TEXT: Build quality/affordable single family homes
Q19: There are many things holding our community back, and it is a complex problem deeply rooted in the community. The community’s high local market, lack of locations to build, the acceptance of the status quo of new, cheaply constructed, small footprint homes that maximize profit and minimize quality, dedication to low income, government subsidized housing that allow landlords to turn a profit but doesn’t bring young professionals  into the community, the dedication to builders in the community that are more concerned about maximizing profit than building quality long term homes, the high local market and need for readjustment from the realty industry are all variables that need to be addressed to improve our community and our housing options. This doesn’t even account fir the supply chain and the rise in material costs that have effected the industry as well. Thank you for asking this question.
